<section id="about" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lAbout">About Ladakh</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">The <em>Roof of the World</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">Ladakh — the Land of High Passes — is the highest, most arid, most remote and most extraordinary Union Territory in India. Carved out of the former state of Jammu & Kashmir in 2019 and made a separate Union Territory, Ladakh occupies the far northeastern corner of India at an average altitude of 3,500 metres, rising to over 7,000 metres in the Karakoram Range to the north. It shares borders with China (Tibet) to the east and Pakistan to the northwest, making it simultaneously one of India's most strategically sensitive and most spiritually alive regions. The landscape of Ladakh is of a beauty that defies ordinary description — snow-capped peaks of the Himalayas and Karakoram reflected in turquoise glacial lakes, ancient monasteries perched on impossibly steep crags above valleys where prayer flags flutter in the thin cold air, rivers of glacial meltwater rushing through gorges of banded geological strata laid down 50 million years ago when the Indian subcontinent collided with Asia and pushed up the Himalayan range. The two districts of Ladakh — Leh and Kargil — represent two profoundly different cultural worlds. Leh district is the heartland of Tibetan Buddhist culture, where Ladakhi people descended from Tibetan settlers maintain a civilisation thousands of years old: monasteries with butter lamp shrines, lamas in maroon robes, thangka paintings of extraordinary refinement, the resonant sound of the ragdung (6-metre ceremonial horn) and the architecture of Leh Palace and Thiksey Monastery that echo Lhasa's Potala Palace. Kargil district, by contrast, is predominantly Muslim — a Shia Muslim community with roots in Central Asia and Persia, whose culture, music and religious practices connect more to Iran than to Tibet. Ladakh is also one of India's most remarkable adventure destinations — the world's highest motorable road (Khardung La, 5,359m), the extraordinary Chadar Trek on the frozen Zanskar River in winter, motorcycle journeys across the Tibetan plateau landscape and some of the world's finest high-altitude camping and trekking.</p>

  <div class="altitude-note">
    <strong>⚠️ Altitude Warning:</strong> Ladakh's average altitude of 3,500m (Leh: 3,524m) causes Acute Mountain Sickness (AMS) in many visitors. <strong>Essential:</strong> Rest completely for the first 24-48 hours after arriving in Leh. Do not exert yourself. Drink 3-4 litres of water daily. Do not ascend to higher altitude on your first day. Consult a doctor about Diamox (acetazolamide) before travel. People with heart or lung conditions should consult a physician before visiting Ladakh.
  </div>
</section>

